      <text xml:space="preserve">A number of games have been published which are based on the [[Dune universe|''Dune'' universe]] created by [[Frank Herbert]].

==Card games==
* ''[[Dune (card game)|Dune]]'' (1997): [[Collectible card game]] produced by [[Five Rings Publishing Group]]/[[Last Unicorn Games]] and later [[Wizards of the Coast]].&lt;ref name=&quot;Scrye&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.geocities.com/sherlockazulu/dune_scrye.htm |title=''Dune'': Classic CCG|last=Baumrucker, MD|first=Steven|date=May 2003|work=[[Scrye]]|publisher=[[Internet Archive]]|accessdate=May 3, 2004 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20040503002210/http://www.geocities.com/sherlockazulu/dune_scrye.htm |archivedate = May 3, 2004}}&lt;/ref&gt; Each player leads a planetary house, &quot;battling, conniving, and bribing its way to greatness ... players bid for powerful characters, search for the life-prolonging spice [[melange (fictional drug)|melange]], avoid [[sandworm (Dune)|sandworm]]s, engage in interstellar commerce, and, naturally, try to kill each other.&quot;&lt;ref name=&quot;Scrye&quot;/&gt;

==Board games==
* ''[[Dune (board game)|Dune]]'' (1979): [[Avalon Hill]] 
* ''Dune'' (1984): [[Parker Brothers]]

==Role-playing games==
* ''Dune: Chronicles of the Imperium'' (2000): Last Unicorn Games; [[role-playing game]] set in the ''Dune'' universe.&lt;ref name=&quot;RPG Dune&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.rpg.net/news+reviews/reviews/rev_4161.html|title=''Dune: Chronicles of the Imperium'' Capsule Review |last=Guder|first=Derek|date=April 19, 2001|publisher=RPG.net|accessdate=March 18, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; Delayed by legal issues and then a corporate buy-out of Last Unicorn by Wizards of the Coast, a &quot;Limited Edition&quot; run of 3000 copies of a core rule-book was initially published, pending Wizard of the Coast's conversion of the game to its [[d20 System|d20]] [[role-playing game system]] and a subsequent wider release.&lt;ref name=&quot;RPG Dune&quot;/&gt; The company later announced that the game would be discontinued.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.wizards.com/dune/ |title=D20 Product News: ''Dune''|year=2000|publisher=Wizards.com (Internet Archive)|accessdate=January 24, 2001 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20010124104300/http://www.wizards.com/dune/ |archivedate = January 24, 2001}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Video games==&lt;!-- This section is the redirect destination of [[Dune computer and video games]] --&gt;
To date, there have been five licensed ''Dune''-related video games released. There have also been many ''Dune''-based [[MUD]]s (Multi-User Dimension) and [[Web browser|browser]]-based online games, all created and run by fans.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://dune.servint.com/general/about_dunemud.php |title=DuneMUD |publisher=Dune.servint.com |accessdate=March 17, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;
&lt;!-- please only list such games if they have a page on a Wiki with a substantial history of stability and a substantial number of editors (see also [[WP:EL#Links normally to be avoided]]). This is not a link farm. --&gt;

===''Dune'' (1992)===
{{Main|Dune (video game)}}
1992's ''Dune'' from [[Cryo Interactive]]/[[Virgin Interactive]] blends adventure with strategy.&lt;ref name=&quot;Moby Dune&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.mobygames.com/game/dune|title=Game Overview: ''Dune'' (1992)|publisher=Mobygames.com|accessdate=March 17, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;Abandonia Dune&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.abandonia.com/games/46/download/Dune.htm|title=Review: ''Dune'' (1992) - Game download available|publisher=Abandonia.com|accessdate=March 17, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; Loosely following the story of the 1965 novel ''[[Dune (novel)|Dune]]'' and using many visual elements from the 1984 [[Dune (film)|film of the same name]] by [[David Lynch]], the game casts the player as [[Paul Atreides]], with the ultimate goal of driving the [[House Harkonnen|Harkonnen]]s from the planet [[Arrakis|Dune]] and taking control of its valuable export, the [[melange (fictional drug)|spice]].&lt;ref name=&quot;Moby Dune&quot;/&gt; Key to success is the management of spice mining, military forces, and ecology as the player amasses allies and skills.&lt;ref name=&quot;Moby Dune&quot;/&gt;

===''Dune II'' (1992)===
{{Main|Dune II}}
''Dune II: The Building of a Dynasty'', later retitled ''Dune II: The Battle for Arrakis'' for the [[Sega Mega Drive|Mega Drive/Genesis]] port, was released in December 1992 from [[Westwood Studios]]/Virgin Interactive.&lt;ref name=&quot;Moby Dune II&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.mobygames.com/game/dune-ii-the-building-of-a-dynasty|title=Game Overview: ''Dune II: The Building of a Dynasty'' (1992)|publisher=Mobygames.com|accessdate=March 17, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;Abandonia Dune II&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.abandonia.com/games/36/download/Dune2.htm|title=Review: ''Dune II - The Building of a Dynasty'' (1992) - Game download available|publisher=Abandonia.com|accessdate=March 17, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; Often considered to be the first &quot;mainstream modern [[real-time strategy]] game,&quot; ''Dune II'' established many conventions of the genre.&lt;ref name=&quot;Moby Dune II&quot;/&gt; Only loosely connected to the plot of the novels or films, the game pits three interplanetary houses &amp;mdash; the [[House Atreides|Atreides]], the [[House Harkonnen|Harkonnen]]s, and the [[House Ordos|Ordos]] &amp;mdash; against each other for control of the planet [[Arrakis]] and its valuable spice, all while fending off the destructive natural forces of the harsh [[desert planet]] itself.&lt;ref name=&quot;Moby Dune II&quot;/&gt;

===''Dune 2000'' (1998)===
{{Main|Dune 2000}}
''Dune 2000'', a 1998 remake of ''Dune II'' from [[Intelligent Games]]/Westwood Studios/Virgin Interactive, added improved graphics and [[live-action]] [[cutscene]]s.&lt;ref name=&quot;Moby Dune 2000&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.mobygames.com/game/dune-2000|title=Game Overview: ''Dune 2000'' (1998)|publisher=Mobygames.com|accessdate=March 17, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; Though gameplay is similar to its predecessor, ''Dune 2000'' features an enhanced storyline and functionality.&lt;ref name=&quot;Moby Dune 2000&quot;/&gt;

===''Frank Herbert's Dune'' (2001)===
{{Main|Frank Herbert's Dune (video game)}}
Released in 2001 by [[Cryo Interactive]]/[[DreamCatcher Interactive]], ''Frank Herbert's Dune'' is a [[3D computer graphics|3D]] video game based on the 2000 [[Syfy|Sci Fi Channel]] [[Frank Herbert's Dune|miniseries of the same name]].&lt;ref name=&quot;Moby FHD&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.mobygames.com/game/frank-herberts-dune|title=Game Overview: ''Frank Herbert's Dune'' (2001)|publisher=Mobygames.com|accessdate=March 17, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; As Paul Atreides, the player must become leader of the [[Fremen]], seize control of Dune, and defeat the evil [[Vladimir Harkonnen|Baron Harkonnen]].&lt;ref name=&quot;Moby FHD&quot;/&gt; The game was not a commercial or critical success, and Cryo subsequently filed for bankruptcy in July 2002.&lt;ref name=&quot;Moby Cryo&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.mobygames.com/company/cryo-interactive-entertainment|title=Overview: Cryo Interactive Entertainment|publisher=MobyGames.com|accessdate=March 17, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;

===''Emperor: Battle for Dune'' (2001)===
{{Main|Emperor: Battle for Dune}}
''Emperor: Battle for Dune'' (Intelligent Games/Westwood Studios/[[Electronic Arts]]) was released on June 12, 2001.&lt;ref name=&quot;Moby Emperor&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.mobygames.com/game/emperor-battle-for-dune|title=Game Overview: ''Emperor: Battle for Dune'' (2001)|publisher=Mobygames.com|accessdate=March 17, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; A sequel to ''Dune 2000'', the real-time strategy game features 3D graphics and live-action cutscenes and casts players as Atreides, Harkonnens, or Ordos.&lt;ref name=&quot;Moby Emperor&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;Guru Emperor&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.guru3d.com/gamereviews/dune/|title=Review: ''Emperor: Battle for Dune'' (2001)|publisher=Guru3D.com|accessdate=March 17, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;

&lt;div id=&quot;DUNE Generations&quot;/&gt;&lt;div id=&quot;Dune Generations&quot;/&gt;
===''DUNE Generations'' (2001, cancelled)===&lt;!-- This section is the redirect destination of [[DUNE Generations]] and [[Dune Generations]] --&gt;
[[Image:Dune generations logo.png|right|175px|''DUNE Generations'' logo]]
In 2001, [[Cryonetworks]] disclosed information about ''Dune Generations'', an online, 3D real-time strategy game set in the ''Dune'' universe.&lt;ref name=&quot;DG 2001&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.dunegenerations.com/ |title=''DUNE Generations'': Main Page|publisher=DuneGenerations.com (Internet Archive)|accessdate=November 27, 2001 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20011127215041/http://www.dunegenerations.com/ |archivedate = November 27, 2001}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;DG Q&amp;A&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/pc/strategy/dunegenerations/news.html?sid=2766761 |title=''DUNE Generations'' Q&amp;A |date=May 30, 2001 |publisher=Gamespot.com |accessdate=March 17, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; The official website for the upcoming game that featured some concept images, a brief background story and description of the persistent gameworld, and a list of frequently asked questions.&lt;ref name=&quot;DG FAQ&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20011021081521/www.dunegenerations.com/uk/html/faq.htm|title=''DUNE Generations'':FAQ |publisher=DuneGenerations.com (Internet Archive)|accessdate=October 21, 2001}}&lt;/ref&gt; The game would be constructed using Cryo's own online multimedia development framework [[SCOL]].&lt;ref name=&quot;DG Dev&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.dunegenerations.com/uk/html/develop01.htm# |title=''DUNE Generations'': Development|publisher=DuneGenerations.com (Internet Archive)|accessdate=January 5, 2002 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20020105205044/http://www.dunegenerations.com/uk/html/develop01.htm# |archivedate = January 5, 2002}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Within &quot;the infrastructure of a permanent and massive multiplayer world that exists online,&quot; ''DUNE Generations'' would let players assume control of a dynasty in the ''Dune'' universe, with the goal of first mastering the natural resources of their own homeworlds and ultimately rising in power and influence through conflicts and alliances with other player dynasties.&lt;ref name=&quot;DG Q&amp;A&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;DG Concept&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.dunegenerations.com/uk/html/lejeu.htm |title=''DUNE Generations'': Concept|publisher=DuneGenerations.com (Internet Archive)|accessdate=October 19, 2001 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20011019220154/http://www.dunegenerations.com/uk/html/lejeu.htm |archivedate = October 19, 2001}}&lt;/ref&gt; Each of the three available dynasty types &amp;mdash; traders, soldiers, or mercenaries &amp;mdash; would provide a different playing experience, all with the long-term goal of gaining control of Arrakis and its valuable spice.&lt;ref name=&quot;DG Q&amp;A&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;DG Concept&quot;/&gt; 

A preview video [[trailer (film)|trailer]] was released in November 2001.&lt;ref name=&quot;DG trailer&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.thedune.ru/cgi-bin/ccc/counter.pl?dunegen/video/dunegenerations.avi |title=Preview Video Trailer: ''DUNE Generations'' (6 MB) |publisher=Thedune.ru |accessdate=March 17, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; The game was still in the [[alpha testing]] stage in February 2002,&lt;ref name=&quot;DG Test&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20021211010037/www.dune-generations.com/index_uk.htm|title=''DUNE Generations'': Information Previewing|publisher=Dune-Generations.com (Internet Archive)|accessdate=February 25, 2002}}&lt;/ref&gt; and the project was ultimately halted after Cryo filed for bankruptcy in July 2002.&lt;ref name=&quot;Moby Cryo&quot;/&gt;

