'''Dalton Trumbo''' (December 9, 1905 &amp;ndash; September 10, 1976) was an [[United States|American]] [[screenwriter]] and [[novelist]], and one of the [[Hollywood Ten]], a group of film professionals who refused to testify before the [[House Un-American Activities Committee]] (HUAC) in 1947 during the committee's investigation of [[Communist]] influences in the motion picture industry. Trumbo won two [[Academy Awards]] while blacklisted; one originally given to a [[front (identity)|front]] writer, and one awarded to Robert Rich, Trumbo's pseudonym.&lt;ref&gt;[http://web.archive.org/web/20071008054115/http://www.oscars.org/press/pressreleases/2005/05.07.18.html AMPAS Press Release]&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/trivia.html AMPAS Oscar Trivia]&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0874308/bio IMDb.com: Dalton Trumbo.] Retrieved 04-12-2010&lt;/ref&gt;

==Early life and career==
Trumbo was born in [[Montrose, Colorado|Montrose]], [[Colorado]], and graduated from [[Grand Junction High School]] in nearby Grand Junction, Colorado. While still in high school, he worked as a cub reporter for the ''[[Grand Junction Daily Sentinel]]'', covering courts, the high school, the mortuary and civic organizations. He attended the [[University of Colorado at Boulder]] for two years, working as a reporter for the ''Boulder Daily Camera'' and contributing to the campus humor magazine, the yearbook and the campus newspaper.

He got his professional start working for [[Vogue (magazine)|''Vogue'']] magazine.

His first published novel, [[Eclipse (Trumbo)|''Eclipse'']] (1935), about a town and its people, was written in the social realist style and drew on his years in Grand Junction. The book was controversial in Grand Junction and helped give him an infamous reputation in this city. Years after his death he would be honored with a statue in front of the Avalon Theater on Main Street, depicted writing a screenplay in a bathtub.

He started in movies in 1937; by the 1940s, he was one of Hollywood's highest paid writers{{citation needed|date=March 2011}} for work on such films as ''[[Thirty Seconds Over Tokyo]]'' (1944), ''[[Our Vines Have Tender Grapes]]'' (1945), and ''[[Kitty Foyle (film)|Kitty Foyle]]'' (1940), for which he was nominated for an [[Academy Award for Writing Adapted Screenplay]].

Trumbo's 1939 [[anti-war]] novel, ''[[Johnny Got His Gun]]'', won a [[National Book Award]] (then known as an American Book Sellers Award) that year. The novel was inspired by an article Trumbo had read about a Canadian soldier who had lost all his limbs in [[World War I]] and was visited in hospital by the [[Edward VIII of the United Kingdom|Prince of Wales]].&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.sparknotes.com/lit/johnnygun/context.html Sparknotes.com.] Retrieved 04-12-2010&lt;/ref&gt;

In 1939, Trumbo married Cleo Fincher who was born in Fresno on July 17, 1916, and later moved with her divorced mother and her brother and sister to Los Angeles. Cleo Trumbo died of natural causes at the age of 93 on October 9, 2009 in the Bay Area city of Los Altos. At the time she was living with her eldest daughter Mitzi.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news
 | title = Cleo Trumbo dies at 93; wife of blacklisted screenwriter Dalton Trumbo
 | url = http://articles.latimes.com/2009/oct/18/local/me-cleo-trumbo18/2
 | work=Los Angeles Times
 | first=Dennis
 | last=McLellan
 | date=October 18, 2009
}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Involvement with communism==
Trumbo aligned himself with the [[Communist Party USA]] before the 1940s, although he did not join the party until later.{{Citation needed|date=March 2011}} After the outbreak of [[World War II]] in 1939, American communists argued that the United States should not get involved in the war on the side of [[the United Kingdom]], since the [[Molotov-Ribbentrop Pact]] of nonaggression meant that the [[Soviet Union]] was at peace with [[Germany]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2011}} 

In 1941, Trumbo wrote a novel ''The Remarkable Andrew'', in which, in one scene, the ghost of [[Andrew Jackson]] appears in order to caution the United States not to get involved in the war. In a review of the book, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time Magazine]]'' sarcastically wrote, &quot;General Jackson's opinions need surprise no one who has observed [[George Washington]] and [[Abraham Lincoln]] zealously following the Communist Party Line in recent years.&quot;&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,765251,00.html?iid=chix-sphere Counsel from Hollywood], Time Magazine, February 3, 1941&lt;/ref&gt;

Shortly after the [[Operation Barbarossa|1941 German invasion of the Soviet Union]], Trumbo and his publisher decided to suspend reprinting of ''Johnny Got His Gun'' until the end of the war. During the war, Trumbo received letters from individuals &quot;denouncing Jews&quot; and using ''Johnny'' to support their arguments for &quot;an immediate negotiated peace&quot; with Nazi Germany; Trumbo reported these correspondents to the [[FBI]].&lt;ref name=&quot;pg 5&quot;&gt;Dalton Trumbo. ''Johnny Got His Gun''. Citadel Press, 2000, [http://books.google.com/books?id=LnnMLLk2uU4C&amp;pg=PA5&amp;lpg=PP1&amp;output=html&amp;sig=roPgN-QwCYEEj0YKC0GC5dnEfC8 pg 5], introduction&lt;/ref&gt; Trumbo regretted this decision, which he called &quot;foolish&quot;. After two FBI agents showed up at his home, he understood that &quot;their interest lay not in the letters but in me.&quot;&lt;ref name=&quot;pg 5&quot;/&gt;

Trumbo was a member of the Communist Party USA from 1943 until 1948.&lt;ref&gt;''Naming Names'', [[Victor Navasky]], 2003&lt;/ref&gt; He bragged in ''[[The Daily Worker]]'' that among the films that communist influence in Hollywood had quashed were adaptations of [[Arthur Koestler]]'s [[Anti-communism|anti-communist]] works ''[[Darkness at Noon]]'' and ''The Yogi and the Commissar''.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.reason.com/news/show/27732.html Hollywood's Missing Movies: Why American films have ignored life under communism. - Reason Magazine&lt;!-- Bot generated title --&gt;]&lt;/ref&gt;

===Blacklisting===
{{Main|Hollywood blacklist}}
During the [[McCarthy Era]] in 1947, Trumbo, along with nine other writers and directors, was called before the House Un-American Activities Committee as an unfriendly witness to testify on the presence of communist influence in [[Hollywood]]. Trumbo and the other nine refused to give information. After conviction for [[contempt of Congress]], he was [[Hollywood blacklist|blacklisted]], and in 1950, spent 11 months in prison in the [[federal penitentiary]] in [[Ashland, Kentucky]].

After Trumbo was blacklisted, some Hollywood actors and directors, such as [[Elia Kazan]] and [[Clifford Odets]], agreed to testify and to provide names of fellow communist party members to Congress. Many of those who testified were immediately ostracized and shunned by their former friends and associates.{{Citation needed|date=March 2011}} Trumbo always maintained that those who testified under pressure from HUAC and the studios were equally victims of the [[Second Red Scare|Red Scare]], an opinion for which he was criticized.{{Citation needed|date=August 2008}}

==Later life==
After completing his sentence, Trumbo and his family moved to [[Mexico]] with [[Hugo Butler]] and his wife [[Jean Rouverol]], who had also been blacklisted. There, Trumbo wrote 30 scripts under [[pseudonym]]s, such as ''[[Gun Crazy]]'' (1950), based on a short story by [[MacKinlay Kantor]], who was the front for the screenplay. It was not until 1992 that Trumbo's role was revealed.&lt;ref name=Apostolou&gt;[http://www.mysteryfile.com/Kantor/Crime_Fiction.html John Apostolou, &quot;MacKinlay Kantor&quot;], ''The Armchair Detective'', Spring 1997, republished on ''Mystery File'', accessed 17 Oct 2010&lt;/ref&gt; 

Gradually the blacklist began to be weakened. With the support of [[Otto Preminger]], Trumbo was credited for his screenplay for the 1960 film ''[[Exodus (film)|Exodus]]'', adapted from the novel by [[Leon Uris]]. Shortly thereafter, [[Kirk Douglas]] made public Trumbo's credit for the screenplay for ''[[Spartacus (film)|Spartacus]]'' (1960),&lt;ref name=&quot;Trumbo&quot;&gt;{{imdb title|0889671|Trumbo (2007)}} Retrieved April 25, 2010.&lt;/ref&gt; an event which has been cited as the beginning of the end of the blacklist. Trumbo was reinstated in the [[Writers Guild of America, West]], and was credited on all subsequent scripts.

In 1971, Trumbo directed the [[Johnny Got His Gun (film)|film adaptation of his novel]] ''[[Johnny Got His Gun]]'', which starred [[Timothy Bottoms]], [[Diane Varsi]] and [[Jason Robards]].

One of Trumbo's last films, ''[[Executive Action (film)|Executive Action]]'' (1973), was based on various [[John F. Kennedy assassination conspiracy theories|conspiracy theories]] about the [[John F. Kennedy assassination|Kennedy assassination]].

His account and analysis of the [[Smith Act]] trials is entitled ''The Devil in the Book''.

==Academy Awards==
He won an [[Academy award|Oscar]] for ''[[The Brave One (1956 film)|The Brave One]]'' (1956), written under the name Robert Rich. In 1975, the Academy officially recognized Trumbo as the winner and presented him with a statuette.

In 1993, Trumbo was posthumously awarded the [[Academy Award]] for writing ''[[Roman Holiday (1953 film)|Roman Holiday]]'' (1953). The screen credit and award were previously given to [[Ian McLellan Hunter]], who had been a &quot;front&quot; for Trumbo.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.oscars.org/press/pressreleases/2005/05.07.18.html &quot;Great To Be Nominated&quot; Enjoys a &quot;Roman Holiday&quot;] AMPAS&lt;/ref&gt;

==Death==
He died in [[Los Angeles]] of a [[heart attack]] at the age of 70 on September 10, 1976.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |title=Dalton Trumbo, Film Writer, Dies; Oscar Winner Had Been Blacklisted |url=http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F7091EFE395C137B93C3A81782D85F428785F9 |quote=Dalton Trumbo, the Hollywood screen writer who was perhaps the most famous member of the blacklisted film industry authors called &quot;the Hollywood Ten,&quot; died of a heart attack early today at his home here. He was 70 years old. He donated his body to science.  |publisher=[[New York Times]] |date=September 11, 1976 |accessdate=2008-06-18 | first=Jon | last=Nordheimer}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Family==
Trumbo had three children: one son, filmmaker and screenwriter [[Christopher Trumbo]] who was considered an expert on the Hollywood blacklist;&lt;ref name=latimes&gt;{{cite news|first=Dennis|last=McLellan|title=Christopher Trumbo dies at 70; screen and TV writer whose father was blacklisted|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/jan/12/local/la-me-christopher-trumbo-20110112|work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |publisher= |date=2011-01-12 |accessdate=2011-01-26}}&lt;/ref&gt; and two daughters, photographer Melissa, known as Mitzi, and psychotherapist Nikola.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news
 | title = A Voice From the Blacklist: Documentary Lets Dalton Trumbo Speak
 | url = http://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/11/movies/11trumbo.html?_r=1&amp;oref=slogin
 | work = [[The New York Times]]
 | location = New York
 | date = 2007-09-11
 | accessdate = 2008-01-04
 | author = [[Michael Cieply]]
}}&lt;/ref&gt; Mitzi once had a relationship with actor/comedian [[Steve Martin]]; Martin later confessed that, at that time in his &quot;tunnel-visioned life,&quot; he had never heard of her father.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news
 | title = Personal History: &quot;In the Bird Cage&quot;
 | url = http://www.newyorker.com/reporting/2007/10/29/071029fa_fact_martin
 | work = [[The New Yorker]]
 | location = New York
 | date = 2007-10-29
 | accessdate = 2008-01-04
 | author = [[Steve Martin]]
}}&lt;/ref&gt; In his memoir, ''Born Standing Up'', Martin credits his time spent with the Trumbo family as having aroused his interest in politics and art. Christopher Trumbo died on January 8, 2011, from complications of kidney cancer.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.ktvu.com/entertainment/26464434/detail.html &quot;Son Of Blacklisted Hollywood Writer Trumbo Dies&quot;] (Jan. 12, 2011) KTVU.com. Retrieved 1-12-2011&lt;/ref&gt;

